05472nam a22008295i 9780823291694DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232916947 a10.1515/97808232916942doi  a(DE-B1597)565983  a(OCoLC)1306540268  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aART0150302bisacsh00aGo Figure :bEnergies, Forms, and Institutions in the Early Modern World /ced. by Judith H. Anderson, Joan Pong Linton. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tSpenser’s Giant and the New Science -- tThe Sacramental Neuter and the Missing Body in Robert Southwell’s Poetics -- tReconfiguring Figuring: John Donne as Narrative Poet -- tThe Narrative Turn against Metaphor: Metonymy, Identification, and Roger Boyle’s Parthenissa -- tCaterpillage: Death and Truthiness in Seventeenth-Century Dutch Still Life Painting -- tFiguring Belief: George Herbert’s Devotional Creatures -- tEntertaining Friends: Falstaff ’s Parasitology -- tSkin Merchants: Jack Cade’s Futures and the Figural Politics of Henry VI, Part II -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGo Figure addresses theories of the figure and practices of figuration ranging from classical rhetoric and biblical exegesis to semiotics, psychoanalysis, and socio-politics. Situating theory in history, the essays in this volume focus on verbal and visual texts from the sixteenth to the eighteenth centuries, and they explore science, sacramental poetics, romance and lyric narrative, and the natural world in still lifes, prayer, parasites, and politics. They engage the work of poets, painters, storytellers, and playwrights. While the theories that inform them are many and various, they share a point of reference in the work of Jean-François Lyotard, who theorizes the co-presence in language of the figure and discourse: Lyotard’s figure relates to discourse as image emerges in description, as sense accompanies signification, and as energies shape texts from within. The original essays invited for the volume show how figural energies and forms inhabit both texts and the practices that produce them—how figures are fundamentally in play in the making of subjects, societies, traditions, and institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aART / European.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Judith H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Judith H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerger, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Mary Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubrow, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Lowell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlimp, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHedrick, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPong Linton, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPong Linton, Joan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYates, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZurcher, Amelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cpri